Then stay away from the traditional idea behind bots and go with packet injection… Every server is so unprotected nowadays its very easy to do

Could you give us a sample snippet of a map walk method? I would appreciate it if you gave some examples.

The client contains all the examples you need for constructing the packets, and most if not all servers do not validate your next step so you could force a straight line between you and the destination and the server will happily comply.

And I do believe you’re looking at it like a traditional bot still. The server’s don’t check objects for validity either, so why bother walking? Just tell the server theres an object right in front of you and it believes you

Actually I was trying to design an SYI thing, where there is no actual client gameframe. So far the only thing I have accomplished is login which I’ve ripped from the client, it’s multithreaded and logs in any amount of clients. The part where I’m lost is after you login, I can’t figure out how you can send the server packets because it doesn’t seem to work. I use the standard methods such as stream.createFrame(), stream.writeWordBigEndian(), etc, they don’t do anything.
[/quote]
Are you properly seeding the ISAAC gen? Are you flushing the buffer after each packet? And your idea is spot on for a packet injection bot

hmm would be hard to verify objects. You would have to parse the landscape archives and then verify that the position you are sending with the object packet is an actual location of an object, and then check distance (normally done). Item checking wouldn’t be that hard, though. Like item on item since you keep track of what items the player has.

edit- It’s 5 am here, so I may not be thinking the clearest, but how could you even verify walking? Everything the server builds off of walking is from the packet. The least you could do (not much at all) is make sure that the place they are requesting to walk to is within x distance. afaik you can’t view a whole entire region in the minimap, so you couldn’t use that.

If you’re talking about server side, then yes. The map files also contain whether each tile is walkable or not, so that with checking if an unpassable object is in your way would pretty much stop all crude attempts. Client side it doesn’t matter, you just tell it what you want it to do[/quote]
